n; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Fir=
e chemistry &amp; severity</span></u><span style=3D""><br></span><span style=
=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers s=
tored in the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escalati=
on to a second alarm; ASURNZ also records cavity smoke migration and roof-ed=
ge heat (deformed soffit, melted gutter). Smoke odour remains three months l=
ater. Taken together, these factors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/=
acidic residues and deep smoke penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof a=
ssembly, and HVAC, so a visual-only approach is not appropriate.</span><span=
 style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div>=
<div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"=
><span style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">As such, could you please provide a=
 written, insurer-funded plan and schedule setting out methods/standards, pa=
ss criteria, dates, and named leads. The detailed methodology and acceptance=
 thresholds are to be designed and agreed by the appropriate independent exp=
erts (hygienist, CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspec=
tor, certifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a moist=
ure/corrosion specialist) and laboratories. &nbsp;Also it is my understandin=
g that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reinstatement practice note) expects in=
trusive investigation and formal sign-offs where the primary structure or ex=
ternal moisture/fire systems are affected, including removal of wet linings/=
insulation, a CPEng report on the impact to the primary structure, LBP desig=
n/supervision where applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><span s=
tyle=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><d=
iv style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><=
span style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">I also believe that at a minimum&nbsp=
;the plan should address intrusive verification of roof/eaves (including und=
erlay, battens, fixings, and truss nail-plates, with perimeter residue/corro=
sivity checks where odour is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor s=
outh/west elevations and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hyg=
ienist clearance before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance fo=
r heat-pump heads and the roof-space gas unit/any ducting; whole-installatio=
n electrical verification to AS/NZS 3000 with certification; plumbing system=
 integrity testing and disinfection where indicated; moisture logging and co=
rrosion/pH-chloride screening of representative framing/fasteners and masonr=
y; and independent IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and re-occupation=
.</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p>=
</span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos,=
 sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Scope adequacy</span></u><span style=3D"">=
<br>=46rom the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into first-floor c=
avities with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge hea=
t with deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope appea=
rs focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal, selective electrical checks=
, =E2=80=9Ctest &amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas) rather than the real damage=
 pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, corrosion).<br>Respectfully, i=
t is not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromised. Non-charred=
 structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar exposed to smoke=
 and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutralised or replaced=
.</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p>=
</span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos,=
 sans-serif;"><span style=3D"">Accordingly, could you please explain and evi=
