pan style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><p>Hi Grant,</p=
><p>I am following up on our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left the me=
eting feeling quite confused about several points, and I would be grateful i=
f you could please clarify the following so I can properly understand the ap=
proach Tower is taking:</p><p><b>1. Independent expert testing</b></p><p>You=
 indicated that Tower/you will not pay for any expert testing as part of my p=
reparation of the claim, as you said that is what you are already doing. How=
ever, I am struggling to understand this position. =46rom my perspective, yo=
u are preparing the claim from Tower=E2=80=99s side, and I have not been inv=
ited to or involved in any of the NZRSC<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space"=
>&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">[can you please clari=
fy what NZRSC stands for? =E2=80=93 I am sorry, I am not familiar with this a=
cronym]<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span>assessments=
 or discussions. This does not feel independent or transparent from my side.=
<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb=
(0, 112, 192);">Attached are the material damage Report &amp; Scope of repai=
r works as provided by our technical Building consultant. These are provided=
 to you for your reference and review. I received these from ASURNZ o Friday=
 5<sup>th</sup><span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>September.=
 &nbsp;</span></p><p>Given the seriousness of the fire, and the chemical inv=
olvement (including spa chemicals with corrosive chlorides and bromides), I a=
m concerned that critical risks may be under-assessed. Could you please clar=
ify why Tower would not support me in engaging independent engineers, hygien=
ists, or other specialists to provide an impartial view?<span class=3D"Apple=
-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">We c=
an provide independent swab-testing by a forensic scientist, which tests for=
 chemical contamination which has occurred from the fire. I would need to me=
et with you to have you provide context and detail on exactly what chemicals=
 were present and where they were located within the property. I am happy to=
 progress this process further with you as soon as possible =E2=80=93 but I w=
ill need to establish more context and detail as to what this potential cont=
amination may be, before we undertake any testing. We can also share the met=
hodology of the forensic testing with you before we undertake the testing. &=
nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p>Further, I request that I be&nbsp;included in all c=
ommunications with any assessors&nbsp;and 3rd parties=E2=80=94 including tex=
ts, emails, calls, and meetings =E2=80=94 and that these be scheduled so I h=
ave the opportunity to participate. This is essential for transparency and t=
o ensure I am properly informed about the basis of decisions being made.<spa=
n class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 1=
12, 192);">I can accommodate this as much as is practically possible. I have=
 kept you fully informed of every step and process that I have undertaken to=
 date when progressing your claim. I understand that you have made a privacy=
 request to our claims department =E2=80=93 which will provide you with acce=
ss to all communications regarding your claim. I will forward this request t=
hat you have made to a<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><u>=
Senior Claims Manager</u><span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>=
=E2=80=93 so that they can respond to your request in a more comprehensive r=
esponse. This is a Claims Management request =E2=80=93 whereas my focus is o=
n the structural repairs required for your claim. Please allow to forward an=
d escalate this request for you. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p><b>2. Struc=
tural elements =E2=80=93 linings and framing</b></p><p>You mentioned that, i=
n addition to demolishing and rebuilding the closed deck, your intention is t=
o replace only a couple of structural beams and to rely on methods such as d=
ry-ice blasting and thermal fogging for the bricks. =46rom a technical persp=
ective, this seems inadequate because:</p><div><ol start=3D"1" type=3D"1" st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; fo=
nt-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12=
pt;">Smoke odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=94 the le=
ast affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after the fire, sugges=
ting deep penetration.<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><o:=
p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size:=
 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">The=
 fire involved spa chemicals, creating corrosive residues (chlorides, bromid=
es) likely absorbed into linings, timber framing, and fixings.<span class=3D=
"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);=
">I have responded to this as above.</span><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D=
"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-=
serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">Superficial cleaning, fogging, or p=
ainting over residues cannot ensure long-term safety or durability.<o:p></o:=
p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt;=
 font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">Bricks an=
d mortar are porous: once penetrated by smoke and chemical residues, they ca=
n continue to off-gas and deteriorate over time, undermining both habitabili=
ty and structural performance.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal"=
 style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><sp=
an style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoN=
ormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif=
;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">Similarly, timber framing, structural ti=
mbers, and plasterboard linings are fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke and ch=
emical residues penetrate, they may release odours, compromise air quality, a=
ccelerate corrosion of embedded fixings, and create conditions for hidden mo=
uld or decay. These risks cannot be fully eliminated by surface cleaning<o:p=
></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 1=
0pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">Your a=
pproach appears to focus only on visible damage (e.g. darkened beams), while=
 overlooking non-visible but equally serious fire, smoke, and water impacts.=
 This is not appropriate, creates significant long-term risks, and is not al=
igned with Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the house to an =E2=80=9C=
as new=E2=80=9D standard.<o:p></o:p></span></li></ol></div><div><div style=3D=
"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D=
"font-size: 12pt;">On that basis, could you clarify how retaining contaminat=
ed bricks, timbers, and linings meets Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstat=
e the property to a =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing and cert=
ification is planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a saf=
e and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div>=
<div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"=
><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><=
div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">=
<b><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">3. Roof assessment</span></b><span style=
=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><p>You indicated that th=
e roof requires no work. I find this difficult to reconcile with the evidenc=
e<span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">: [ with respect I said that there=
 was no structural fire damage in the roof space. It could be accepted that t=
here is a faint smoke odour in the roof space from any smoke which may have p=
assed through this space. We have allowed for replacement of 95 sqm of ceili=
ng insulation to eliminate the possibility of any smoke odours remaining.</s=
pan><span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><ol start=3D=
"1" type=3D"1" style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D=
"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D=
"font-size: 12pt;">Large volumes of black smoke were seen coming out from al=
l sides of the roof during the fire.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoN=
ormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif=
;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">A gutter was significantly heat-damaged.=
<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-si=
ze: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 112, 192);"><span st=
yle=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: windowtext;">Local reporting even suggested t=
he fire appeared to be in the roof. I have been in the roof space.<span clas=
s=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=3D"font-size: 12=
pt;">There is no structural fire damage in the roof space.<span class=3D"App=
le-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p>If external h=
eat was sufficient to damage guttering, then internal elements such as roof c=
avity insulation, underlay, battens, fixings, and trusses may also have been=
 affected. Could you please clarify what inspection methods were used to con=
clude the roof was undamaged? Were cavity inspections, intrusive checks, or r=
esidue/chemical tests undertaken? What testing and certification is planned t=
o ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=
=80=9D condition?</p><p><b>4. Services =E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water=
</b></p><p>I understand that you are going to test the gas unit and propose a=
 plan to bring it up to new standard, which I appreciate. However, could you=
 also please clarify what is planned for the &nbsp;electricty system, which s=
uffered significant and widespread damage and the water distribution system<=
/p><p>At present I am unclear how these critical services will be properly t=
ested and reinstated. What testing and certification is planned to ensure th=
ese critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D co=
ndition?</p><p><b>5. Timing and completeness of assessments</b></p><p>I am a=
lso confused and &nbsp;concerned that a repair plan is already being discuss=
ed before full assessments have been completed and before I have seen the NZ=
RSC or other formal reports.</p><p>Could you clarify why Tower is progressin=
g toward a repair plan at this stage rather than awaiting intrusive testing,=
 particularly given the involvement of corrosive chemicals and deep smoke pe=
netration? What testing and certification is planned to ensure these critica=
l services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? An=
d what would be the sequencing of those to inform a realistic plan?</p><p>In=
 addition, is it not too risky to wait until after restructuring works to de=
termine whether the house is safe and meets code requirements? That approach=
 could prolong reinstatement unnecessarily, leaving me at greater disadvanta=
ge with accommodation costs and delays that are outside my control.&nbsp;</p=
><p><b>6. Testing and reporting</b></p><p>Could you please confirm:</p><ol s=
tart=3D"1" type=3D"1" style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" s=
tyle=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span=
 style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">What tests or assessments have actually been com=
pleted so far?<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin=
: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font=
-size: 12pt;">Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, no intrusive test=
ing has been arranged?<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D=
"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D=
"font-size: 12pt;">When the NZRSC report and other reports will be made avai=
lable to me?<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0=
in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-si=
ze: 12pt;">What testing and certification is planned to ensure my house rest=
ored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And could you please p=
rovide sequencing and timings.<o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p><b>7. Accommoda=
tion support -<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></b><span s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">Claims Manager will answer these questions=
 for you.<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span></p><div>=
&nbsp;<br class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><p>A number of critical a=
ssessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 including tests for chemical penetra=
tion, the roof structure and cavity, and essential services such as electric=
ity and water. Until these are properly completed and confirmed, the house i=
s uninhabitable.</p><p>At present, my rental accommodation is being funded u=
nder the contents policy ($30,000 limit). However, with reinstatement not ye=
t underway and key assessments still pending, it is clear this allowance wil=
l be insufficient. These delays are entirely outside my control.</p><p>The Fa=
ir Insurance Code requires insurers to act fairly and not disadvantage custo=
mers through delay. The principle of insurance is to restore the insured to t=
he pre-loss position. To avoid being placed at a further disadvantage, I wou=
ld like to explore the following options:</p><ol start=3D"1" type=3D"1" styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font=
-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt=
;">Option A: Tower agrees I may take the lead in arranging necessary assessm=
ents and reinstatement works, provided all works are to =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=
=9D standard, meet current Building Code requirements, and remain within the=
 insured sum. Tower would reimburse incurred costs within 15 days of invoice=
 on a monthly basis, ensuring timely progress without administrative delay.<=
o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-siz=
e: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">O=
ption B: Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will continue to cover my acc=
ommodation costs until the house is fully restored and habitable, given that=
 ongoing delays are not of my making.<o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p>Could yo=
u please confirm which of these approaches Tower is prepared to adopt, so th=
at I am not unfairly disadvantaged by circumstances outside my control?</p><=
p><b>8. Privacy Act material =E2=80=93<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">=
&nbsp;</span></b><span style=3D"color: rgb(0, 112, 192);">Claims Manager wil=
l answer these questions for you.<span class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp=
;</span></span></p><p>You previously referred me to information provided und=
er the Privacy Act, which I could not find. I found those two email but the l=
inks I received do not open or function. Could you please resend this inform=
ation, ensuring that the links are accessible, or alternatively provide the d=
ocuments as direct PDF/email attachments?</p><p><b>Summary point</b></p><p>A=
t present, I remain unclear how Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=80=94 w=
hich appears to favor superficial cleaning and limited replacement =E2=80=94=
 can reasonably restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=
=80=9D standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical penetration o=
f bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions regarding the roof s=
tructure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full reinstatement of essent=
ial services such as electricity, water, and gas.</p><p>I would greatly appr=
eciate your clarification on each of these points so that I can properly und=
erstand how my home will be restored to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=
=80=9D standard,</p><p>Kind regards,</p><p>Raffaella del Prete</p><div><div s=
tyle=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span=
 style=3D"font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><blockq=
